            <div type="translation">
            <p>To the divine shades of Lucius Cassius Colonus Colonianus, a Roman knight. He lived 35 years.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Other bibliography: C. Vermeule, “Greek, Roman and Etruscan Sculptures: The Benjamin and Lucy Rowland Collection,” The Burlington Magazine (London 1974) 409</p>
                <p>Line 1: D of Dis slightly below rest of letters in line. Possibly missing triangular interpunct at end of line, however portion of lid is weathered.</p>
                <p>Line 2: second N of ann(is) irregularly wider than first N, followed by irregularly wider spacing between ann(is) and XXXV and wider spacing between letters X and V. These irregularities contribute to an uncentered second line closer to the right margin.</p>
                <p>Letters of line 1 (1-1.2) are smaller in size compared to letters of line 2 (1.5-1.7).</p>
                <p>The identity of Colonianus is not known. However, the cognominal suffix “-anus” and doubling of Colonus and Colonianus may suggest a reference to an ancestor (instead of adoption) of an agnatic family. The cognomen Colonus also suggests some ancestral connection to agriculture or being a “colonist” (perhaps identifying Colonianus as an original member of a colony), but further cannot be known. There has been some discussion questioning the authenticity of the urn by Matz, but the claim has been rejected by Sinn and Vermuele.</p>
                <p>Transcription from photo and handwritten transcription from G. Alfödy.</p>
            </div>
            

